<Base title="Sources" compactHeader={true}>
  <h2>Sources</h2>
  <p>Every topic on this site is built from answers published on the four sources below. They were chosen because their answering scholars are formally trained in the four madhāhib and the two creedal schools (Ashʿarī and Māturīdī) — the scholarly mainstream of Sunnī Islam since the early Islamic centuries.</p>

  <h3>SeekersGuidance</h3>
  <p><a href="https://seekersguidance.org/" rel="noopener external">seekersguidance.org</a> — Founded by Shaykh Faraz Rabbani, with a roster of scholars across all four madhāhib. Strong on Ḥanafī fiqh, Ashʿarī ʿaqīdah, and traditional spirituality.</p>

  <h3>IslamQA.org</h3>
  <p><a href="https://islamqa.org/" rel="noopener external">islamqa.org</a> — The Deobandī Ḥanafī Q&amp;A site overseen by Mufti Taqi Usmani's affiliated network of dār al-iftāʾ institutions. (Distinct from the unrelated islamqa.info, which is Salafī-aligned.)</p>

  <h3>Ask Imam</h3>
  <p><a href="https://askimam.org/" rel="noopener external">askimam.org</a> — Madrasah-In'aamiyyah's Q&amp;A platform, led by Mufti Ebrahim Desai (raḥimahullāh). Ḥanafī, traditionalist.</p>

  <h3>hadithanswers.com</h3>
  <p><a href="https://hadithanswers.com/" rel="noopener external">hadithanswers.com</a> — Dedicated to ḥadīth verification and grading from the classical Sunnī tradition; useful for sourcing the chains of reports that come up in disputes.</p>
</Base>
